<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">free</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span> <span class="o">...</span> <span class="p">}</span>

<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">is_live</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">-&gt;</span> <span class="nb">bool</span> <span class="p">{</span><span class="o">...</span><span class="p">}</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">new</code> ,ô <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code>,ô and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get</code> functions can be easily implemented similarly with this structure, setting each entryãs <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">item</code> field to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">None</code> when they areô free,ô andô toô <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Some(value)</code> whenô theyô areô allocated.ô Note that <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">new</code> now requires an additional argument, the initial value of the allocated entry.ô We <em>move</em> the ownership to the allocator because we donãt want another reference to the same entityô lying around there.</p>

<p>Also note that <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get</code> functions can tell if the entity is aliveô or not, solving the use-after-free problem we had before.</p>

<p>The problem with this implementation is that, due toô Rustãsô ownership rules,ô now weô canãt use multiple mutable referencesô at the same timeô using the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get_mut</code> function multiple times, which is a big problem when we want to implement operations between entities. Consider the following code:ô </p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nd">#[derive(Debug,</span> <span class="nd">Default)]</span>
<span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">Entity</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="n">id</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="n">name</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">String</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="n">is_active</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">bool</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">generational_array</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">GenerationalIndexArray</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">e1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generational_array</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s">"e1"</span><span class="nf">.to_string</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">is_active</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="k">false</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">id</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nn">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">()});</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">e2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generational_array</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="n">name</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s">"e2"</span><span class="nf">.to_string</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">is_active</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="k">false</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">id</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nn">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">()});</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generational_array</span><span class="nf">.get_mut</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">e1</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generational_array</span><span class="nf">.get_mut</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">e2</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">();</span> <span class="c">// Error!</span>
