<p>In this case, the borrow checker is complaining because we have two mutable references to memory owned by the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">generational_array</code> variable.ô </p>

<p>If you think about it, it makes sense to provide access to many mutable references to entries within theô allocator,ô because the <strong>allocator couldnãt care less about the current state of the memory it manages</strong>, itô only cares about which entries areô free,ô and the generation for each entry. The problem is thatô Rustô doesnãt know about this!ô </p>

<h1 id="refcell-to-the-rescue">RefCell to the rescue</h1>

<p>The borrow checker wonãt allow usô to haveô multiple references to a memory segment owned by the memory allocator, even though we know that the referenced segments are disjoint.</p>

<p>Since this is a memory allocator, what we need is:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Many references to multiple segments of the internal array</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Mutable access to those references to update entity state</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Thisô can be achieved in safeô Rustô using <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/cell/index.html">RefCell</a>. A <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> Is a <strong>container</strong> that allows you to have multiple references to a memory segment and mutate it using <strong><a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/interior-mutability.html">interior mutability</a></strong>ô </p>

<p>The borrowing rules inô Rustô say that you can have as many references as you want (aliases),ô but only one mutating reference at the time (inherited mutability). The trick with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> is that you take as many immutable references to elements within the array (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell&lt;T&gt;</code>)ô andô each reference implements the function <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">borrow_mut(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;mut T</code> (note the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&amp;self</code> qualifier, denoting an immutable reference to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">self</code>). This function will allow us to mutate the contained value <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">T</code>,ô using <strong>interior mutability</strong>.ô </p>

<p>Letãs see how this works:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c">// New version of array entry, use RefCell&lt;T&gt; instead of just T</span>
<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">GenerationalArrayEntryCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">item</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Option</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">RefCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">u32</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

