<h1 id="what-about-resizing">What about resizing?</h1>

<p>You might have noticed that we are using a <strong>vector</strong> to store our entities, and this is good for performance because the data locality might keep cache misses in check. However, there is a case where our current implementation is inefficient, and thatãs when you <strong>allocate too many entities</strong>, especially if you donãt know how many you might need. If you have to allocate many entitiesô at once, you might have to <strong>request several resize operations</strong> for the vector (implicitly with each <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">push</code>). Since theô actualô dataô is locatedô within the array, each array entry might beô bigô and expensive to copy into a new memory segment.ô </p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Another problem thatãs not so common inô Rustô but is worth being awareô of,ô isô the factô that each resize might <strong>invalidate pointers to positions within the array</strong>.ô Using raw pointers is not common inô Rustô butô if you are writing a game engine, thatãs probably not the craziest thing youô are doing.ô </p>
</blockquote>

<p>If you want cheaper resize operations to handle these cases, you can change the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Option&lt;RefCell&lt;T&gt;&gt;</code> in the array entry to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Box&lt;Option&lt;RefCell&lt;T&gt;&gt;</code>.ô Thisô will allocate objects in the heap and store the pointer, and the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> will allow you to use the same trick to have many mutable references to positions within the same allocator array.</p>

<h1 id="an-alternative-approach-withplacement-new">An alternative approach withãÎô Placement new?</h1>

<p>Up untilô now, we have a functional implementation that you could use for many use cases. In this section, we will implement another version that is functionally the same as the one we already have but uses an interesting feature that will help us later when we try to implement a useful (and very unsafe) trick to implement our pointer type.ô </p>

<p>Consider our current entry type:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">GenerationalArrayEntryCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">u32</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">item</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Option</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">RefCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>In this type,ô we use the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Option&lt;...&gt;</code> part to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">drop</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">init</code>ialize values.ô Notice how we set <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">item</code> to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">None</code> when we free an element? Weãre essentially calling the destructor for that item. Assigning <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">None</code> also allows you to specify that this entry isô in an invalid stateô (because itô was deallocatedô with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code>). However, we donãt need that part, as the initialized stateô is determinedô by the presence of this entry in the free list.ô </p>

<p>So, instead of using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Option</code> to implement destruction and initialization, we will use a different approach. We will allocate <strong>uninitialized memory</strong> and construct and destruct entries there.ô </p>

<p>The problem is thatô Rustô doesnãt allow you to specify the memory address whereô a value will be stored.ô Rust relies on the compilerô being able to findô the final memory location whereô an object should be constructedô andô optimize outô unnecessary copies.ô Consider the following code as an example:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">main</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">Box</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">new</span><span class="p">([[</span><span class="mi">0u64</span><span class="p">;</span> <span class="mi">1_000_000_000</span><span class="p">]]);</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If you run this program with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cargo run</code>,ô it will crash with a stackô overflow,ô because the internal array content overflows the stack. It is constructed in theô stack,ô and then moved into the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Box</code>.ô </p>

<p>On the other hand, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cargo run --release</code> runs with noô problem,ô because the compiler can optimize unnecessary moves and writes the memory content where it should end.ô </p>

<p>Thisô is an extreme exampleô butô itô shows that sometimes itãs hard to control how objectsô are allocatedô in memory. In C++, you would usually solve this problem byô allocatingô a block of memory beforehand and filling it with <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/222557/what-uses-are-there-for-placement-new"><strong>placement new</strong></a>.ô ô </p>

<p>Placement new is a C++ feature that allows you to construct an object inô a memory segmentô thatãs already allocated.ô Thisô is somethingô usefulô in cases like ours where we want to manage our programãs memory ourselves, weô can still construct objects like always but without worrying about requesting and freeing memory unnecessarily.ô </p>

<p>However,ô Rustô doesnãt provide an equivalent language feature to placement new.ô Thisô makes sense if you think about it because being able to place a new object on some pre-existent block of memory implies that you can have <strong>uninitialized memory</strong>, but the rust compiler <strong>does not allow uninitialized variables</strong>,ô and relies heavily on that assumption to implement optimizations and features. But in cases like ours, we can use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code>!</p>

<p>ô <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/mem/union.MaybeUninit.html"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code> </a> is a Rust type provided by the standard library to implement something <em>similar</em> to placement new in C++. It allows you to have <strong>uninitialized blocks of memory</strong>. It tells the compiler that the internal memoryô is not initialized, turning off any optimization that relies on that assumption.ô </p>

<p>You declare a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code> variable as follows:ô </p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">MaybeUninit</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="nb">i32</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">uninit</span><span class="p">();</span>

</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Now <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">x</code> is of type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit&lt;i32&gt;</code>, and <strong>itãs guaranteed to have the same layout as an <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">i32</code></strong>. We can also use this propertyô toô alwaysô keep our objectsô in theô sameô memory location and closer to each other!</p>

<p>Finally, we can implement an allocator using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code>:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nd">#[derive(Default)]</span>
<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">GIABoxUninit</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="k">where</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Default</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">entries</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">GIABoxUninitEntry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">free</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="nb">usize</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">type</span> <span class="n">Generation</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">u32</span><span class="p">;</span>

<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">GIABoxUninitEntry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Generation</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">ptr</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Box</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">MaybeUninit</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>In this implementation, the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">GIABoxUninitEntry</code> replaces the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Option</code> part in the previous one to specify the memory segment whereô the item will be stored. Letãs see how we implement the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">new</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code> functions:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="err">ô </span>
<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">element</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">T</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">-&gt;</span> <span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">if</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.free</span><span class="nf">.is_empty</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="c">// Construct a new entry</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">new_entry</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">InPlaceAllocEntry</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">mem</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nn">MaybeUninit</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">uninit</span><span class="p">(),</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="p">};</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">new_entry_index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="nf">.len</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="c">// Initialize it sinceô it will be retrievedô from this function</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">new_entry</span><span class="py">.ptr</span><span class="nf">.write</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">element</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="c">// Add it to the current list of entries</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="nf">.push</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">new_entry</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">new_entry_index</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="p">};</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="p">}</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">next_free</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.free</span><span class="nf">.pop</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entry</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">next_free</span><span class="p">];</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="c">// Initialize entry, don't return uninitialized memory</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">entry</span><span class="py">.ptr</span><span class="nf">.write</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">element</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">next_free</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">entry</span><span class="py">.generation</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="p">};</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Here we use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">write</code> to store the elementãs memory within theô allocator,ô instead of filling the entry with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Some(element)</code>.ô Note that <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit::write</code> takes ownership of the argument.ô </p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">free</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="o">!</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="nf">.is_live</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>
        <span class="nd">panic!</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s">"Trying to free already unused index"</span><span class="p">);</span>
    <span class="p">}</span>
    <span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="py">.index</span><span class="p">;</span>
    <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.free</span><span class="nf">.push</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">);</span>
    <span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entry</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">GIABoxUninitEntry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">];</span>
    <span class="n">entry</span><span class="py">.generation</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">;</span>
    <span class="k">unsafe</span> <span class="p">{</span>
        <span class="n">entry</span><span class="py">.ptr</span><span class="nf">.assume_init_drop</span><span class="p">();</span>
    <span class="p">}</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>And we reached the first <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">unsafe</code> in this article. As for the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code>ô functionô we use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">assume_init_drop</code> to call the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">drop</code> function of the dataô thatô wasô storedô in that entry. This operation is unsafe because the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code> canãt ensure that the underlying memory is initialized, so calling the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">drop</code> method could result in panic or undefined behavior.ô We know thatô itãs initializedô because itãs alive, butô this is something we have to ensureô with our own logic.ô </p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">-&gt;</span> <span class="nb">Option</span><span class="o">&lt;&amp;</span><span class="n">RefCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="o">!</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="nf">.is_live</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="nb">None</span><span class="p">;</span>
    <span class="p">}</span>
    <span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entry</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="py">.index</span><span class="p">];</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="k">unsafe</span> <span class="p">{</span>
        <span class="nf">Some</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="py">.index</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="py">.ptr</span><span class="nf">.assume_init_ref</span><span class="p">())</span>
    <span class="p">};</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>And finally, in the get function, we canô justô ask for a mutable reference to the internal memory. Similarly to the previous cases, in the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get</code>ô functionô we use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">assume_init</code> because we know that the entryô is initializedô (is <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">live</code>).</p>

<p>So we have gainedãÎô Nothing yet, itãsô just a refactor introducing unsafe calls. However, this approach will prove helpful later!</p>

<h1 id="improving-ergonomics-with-raw-pointers">Improving ergonomics with raw pointers</h1>

<p>Now that we have some solidô implementations,ô letãs check how we use this codeô in action!</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c">// Our dummy entity type</span>
<span class="nd">#[derive(Default)]</span>
<span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">Entity</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="n">id</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">usize</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="err">ô </span>
    <span class="n">is_active</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">bool</span><span class="p">,</span>
    <span class="n">name</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">String</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="c">// Constructing the allocator and creating an entity</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">gbu</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">GIABoxUninit</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_handle</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gbu</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nn">Entity</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">());</span>

<span class="c">// Initializing the entity:</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gbu</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="k">assert</span><span class="o">!</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.is_some</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.borrow_mut</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="py">.id</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">42</span><span class="p">;</span>
<span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="py">.name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">"test1"</span><span class="nf">.to_owned</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="py">.is_active</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="k">true</span><span class="p">;</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Constructing the allocator is not hard, weô justô call the constructor once at the start of our program, and then we use that same instance everywhere.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Creating an entity is also easy, weô justô use the new function that takes the ownership of a new entity we pass as argument.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>However, using an entity implies:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Getting a reference to the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> from the handle and the allocator</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Checking if the entity is valid with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">is_some</code>,ô but you can jump to unwrap if you donãt care about crashing the app on an invalid pointer</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>getting a mutable reference to the actual entity from the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Finallyô usingô the entity</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Using an entity is not only cumbersome, but we might run into borrow-checking issues if we want to free it:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">allocator</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">GIABoxUninit</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_handle</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">bgu</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nn">Entity</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="c">// Initializing the entity:</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">allocator</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span> <span class="c">// immutable borrow of "allocator"</span>
<span class="k">assert</span><span class="o">!</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.is_some</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.borrow_mut</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="n">allocator</span><span class="nf">.free</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c">// ERROR: Mutable Borrow of "allocator"</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If we would like to do something like this for whatever reason, we wouldô be forcedô to scope the entity reference to prevent borrowing issues:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">allocator</span><span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">GIABoxUninit</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_handle</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">bgu</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nn">Entity</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="n">allocator</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span> <span class="c">// inmutable borrow of "allocator"</span>
    <span class="k">assert</span><span class="o">!</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.is_some</span><span class="p">());</span>
    <span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">entity_ref</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.borrow_mut</span><span class="p">();</span>
    <span class="c">// Do something with entity_ref...</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="n">allocator</span><span class="nf">.free</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c">// OK: previous borrow is out of scope</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>SoãÎô yeah,ô notô particularlyô comfortable to use.ô In the next section, weô will work on better usability for our entity allocators.ô </p>

<h2 id="improving-handle-usability">Improving handle usability</h2>

<p>Notice that the allocator manages the lifetime of storedô objects,ô with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">new</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code>, but it doesnãt care about what isô beingô doneô with that memory. Therefore, we can affordô usô a bit more flexibility if we allow <strong>unrestricted access to that memory through pointers</strong>.</p>

<p>Consider the following implementation:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nd">#[derive(Debug,</span> <span class="nd">Default)]</span>
<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">InPlaceAllocator</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="k">where</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">T</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Default</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">entries</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">InPlaceAllocEntry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">free</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="nb">usize</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="nd">#[derive(Debug)]</span>
<span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">InPlaceAllocEntry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">value</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">RefCell</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">MaybeUninit</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Generation</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Notice how the type of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">value</code> in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">InPlaceAllocEntry</code> is <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell&lt;MaybeUninit&lt;T&gt;&gt;</code>,ô meaning that values are stored contiguously in memory.ô </p>

<p>Nowô theô implementation:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">impl</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">InPlaceAllocator</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">fn</span> <span class="nf">get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">GenerationalIndex</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">-&gt;</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">T</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="nd">debug_assert!</span><span class="p">(</span>
ô  ô  ô  ô  ô  ô ô <span class="k">self</span><span class="nf">.is_live</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">),</span>
ô  ô  ô  ô  ô  ô ô <span class="s">"Trying to retrieve uninitialized memory"</span>
ô  ô  ô  ô ô <span class="p">);</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entry</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="k">self</span><span class="py">.entries</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="py">.index</span><span class="p">];</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="k">return</span> <span class="k">unsafe</span> <span class="p">{</span> <span class="n">entry</span><span class="py">.value</span><span class="nf">.borrow_mut</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.as_mut_ptr</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.as_mut</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="nf">.unwrap</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="p">};</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="p">}</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code>,ô <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">new</code>,ô andô <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">is_live</code> are similar to the previous versions</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>In <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get</code>,ô we introduce an unsafe call to get a raw pointer to the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit</code>ãs internal memory, and then we convert it to a mutable reference</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Notice how <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> isô importantô in this case, allowing us to get a mutable reference to something behind an immutable reference</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>We removed the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Option&lt;...&gt;</code> from the return type to further improve the ergonomics of this API, but you can keep it if it fits better your usage patterns</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>With this simple change, we also get an interesting property: The borrow checker can now help us prevent a few errors:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="c">// Create an allocator and a handle</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">InPlaceAllocator</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_handle</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nn">entity</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="c">// Inmutable borrow of inplace_alloc</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="c">//Try to get a mutable borrow of inplace_alloc</span>
<span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.free</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>In this example, we get a reference to the entity in a single call, but ifô we try to free the underlying entity, the compiler willô complain,ô because of borrow checking issues: We try to get a mutable reference with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">free</code> to the allocator, whichô was immutably borrowedô when we got our entity reference.</p>

<p>A possible danger with this approach is that you can have <strong>multiple mutable references to the same entity</strong> without realizing it, theô compiler canãt save you here:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">let</span> <span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nn">InPlaceAllocator</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">entity</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">();</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_handle</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.new</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nn">entity</span><span class="p">::</span><span class="nf">default</span><span class="p">());</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_ref1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="k">let</span> <span class="n">entity_ref2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">inplace_alloc</span><span class="nf">.get</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">entity_handle</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="c">// Compiles with no problem, youô can use both references as you want</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>You have to be careful withô how you allowô access to handles if you want your system to be safe!</p>

<h2 id="abasicpointer-type">Aô basicô pointer type</h2>

<p>In this section, we will use a slightly different approach that will allow us to have our custom pointer type, so we donãt even need a reference to the original allocator:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nd">#[derive(Default)]</span>
<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">BoxAllocator</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="n">entries</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="nb">Box</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">Entry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
    <span class="n">free</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">Vec</span><span class="o">&lt;*</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">Entry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="p">}</span>

<span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">Entry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Generation</span><span class="p">,</span>
    <span class="n">value</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">MaybeUninit</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Each entityô is storedô in an <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Entry</code> with a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">generation</code> field asô metadata,ô and a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">value</code> field as the actual entity. Those entries are <strong>stored within a Box</strong> because we want the entries to remain in the heap. Specifically, we need to prevent resizes of the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">entries</code> vector in the allocator from messing with pointers. If we store a raw pointer to a position within the vector, a resize could reallocate the entry to another memory addressô andô our pointer would be invalidated.ô This problem could be solvedô with a list-of-arrays data structure instead of a vector, butô weô wonãt go thereô in this article.ô </p>

<p>Notice that the type of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">value</code> in the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Entry</code> struct is just <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">MaybeUninit&lt;T&gt;</code>,ô thereãs no <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">RefCell</code> as before. We do thisô because we wantô to allow unrestricted access to the internal memory. Since this is an allocator, the allocator doesnãt care about what isô being doneô with the memory it stores, itô only cares about what memory segments are free or not.ô </p>

<p>As previously mentioned, ensuring memory consistency is a responsibility of the system using the allocator!</p>

<p>On the other hand, our pointer type will be like this:</p>

<div class="language-rust highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">pub</span> <span class="k">struct</span> <span class="n">EntityPtr</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="p">{</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">generation</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">Generation</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="err">ô </span> <span class="err">ô ô </span><span class="n">ptr</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">*</span><span class="k">mut</span> <span class="n">Entry</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="c">// super unsafe raw pointer!</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Where theô <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ptr</code> value corresponds to the internal memory address within the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Box&lt;Entry&lt;T&gt;&gt;</code> in the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Allocator</code>. Itãs quite important to prevent the user from constructing an <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">EntityPtr</code> by themselves, youô should restrict the access to this type such that the only way to get a pointer is from the allocator:</p>

